# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: symfony
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] The **Doctrine Project** (or **Doctrine**) is a set of PHP libraries primarily focused on providing persistence services and related functionality.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Its most commonly known projects are the object–relational mapper (ORM) and the database abstraction layer it is built on top of.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] One of Doctrine's key features is the option to write database queries in Doctrine Query Language (DQL), an object-oriented dialect of SQL.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Developers of two major PHP frameworks, Symfony and Laminas have official out-of-the-box support for Doctrine, while 3rd party Doctrine packages are available for Laravel, CodeIgniter and others.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Entities in Doctrine 2 are lightweight PHP Objects that contain persistable properties.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Doctrine 1.x follows the active record pattern for working with data, where a class corresponds with a database table.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] One feature of Doctrine is the low level of configuration that is needed to start a project.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Doctrine can generate object classes from an existing database, and the programmer can then specify relations and add custom functionality to the generated classes.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] There is no need to generate or maintain complex XML database schemas, as seen in many other frameworks.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Another key feature of Doctrine is the ability to optionally write database queries in an OO (object oriented) SQL dialect called **DQL** (Doctrine Query Language) inspired by Hibernate's HQL.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Alternately, the QueryBuilder class (Doctrine_Query in Doctrine 1.x) allows one to construct queries through a fluent interface.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] These interfaces provide developers with powerful alternatives to SQL which maintain flexibility and still allow for switching of database back-ends, without requiring any code duplication.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Writing queries explicitly however is not always necessary, as Doctrine performs joins and fetches related objects automatically.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Small projects can be easily constructed without writing queries.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Doctrine was started by Konsta Vesterinen, also known as *zYne-*.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] The project's initial commit was made on April 13, 2006.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] As the project became more mature, the adoption began to pick up.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Before long, the community was active and development was receiving regular contributions, among others from the Google Summer of Code project.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Doctrine 1.0.0 was released on September 1, 2008.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] The first stable version of Doctrine 2.0 was released on December 22, 2010, after 2.5 years of dedicated development starting in early 2008.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Doctrine has been influenced by dozens of projects and many different people.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] The largest influences have been the Java ORM solution Hibernate and the ActiveRecord architecture used in Ruby on Rails.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] The purpose of the Doctrine project is to build an equally powerful solution for the PHP language for high-load websites that have to maintain a constant flow of visitors.
[src:symfony/doctrine-php] Doctrine ORM can be used to improve the performance of such websites.
