[src:symfony/page-creation] `/about`) to your page and points to a controller.
[src:symfony/page-creation] Check out the Cosmic Coding with Symfony screencast series.
[src:symfony/page-creation] Symfony *embraces* the HTTP Request-Response lifecycle.
[src:symfony/page-creation] To find out more, see Symfony and HTTP Fundamentals.
[src:symfony/page-creation] Before continuing, make sure you've read the Setup article and can access your new Symfony app in the browser.
[src:symfony/page-creation] Suppose you want to create a page - `/lucky/number` - that generates a lucky (well, random) number and prints it.
[src:symfony/page-creation] Now you need to associate this controller function with a public URL (e.g.
[src:symfony/page-creation] `/lucky/number`) so that the `number()` method is called when a user browses to it.
[src:symfony/page-creation] Symfony recommends defining routes as attributes to have the controller code and its route configuration at the same location.
[src:symfony/page-creation] However, if you prefer, you can define routes in separate files using the YAML or PHP formats.
[src:symfony/page-creation] If you see a lucky number being printed back to you, congratulations!
