[src:symfony/page-creation] One of Symfony's *amazing* features is the Web Debug Toolbar: a bar that displays a *huge* amount of debugging information along the bottom of your page while developing.
[src:symfony/page-creation] This is all included by default when using a Symfony pack called `symfony/profiler-pack`.
[src:symfony/page-creation] You will see a dark bar along the bottom of the page.
[src:symfony/page-creation] You'll learn more about all the information it holds along the way, but feel free to experiment: hover over and click the different icons to get information about routing, performance, logging and more.
[src:symfony/page-creation] If you're returning HTML from your controller, you'll probably want to render a template.
[src:symfony/page-creation] Fortunately, Symfony comes with Twig: a templating language that's minimal, powerful and actually quite fun.
[src:symfony/page-creation] Now, use the handy `render()` method to render a template.
[src:symfony/page-creation] Template files live in the `templates/` directory, which was created for you automatically when you installed Twig.
