[src:symfony/routing-p01] When your application receives a request, it calls a controller action to generate the response.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The routing configuration defines which action to run for each incoming URL.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] It also provides other useful features, like generating SEO-friendly URLs (e.g.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] `/read/intro-to-symfony` instead of `index.php?article_id=57`).
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Routes can be configured in YAML, PHP or using attributes.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] All formats provide the same features and performance, so choose your favorite.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Symfony recommends attributes because it's convenient to put the route and controller in the same place.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] PHP attributes allow you to define routes next to the code of the controllers associated with those routes.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Attributes are enabled by default in Symfony applications that use Symfony Flex, so you can start using them right away.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] This tells Symfony to look for `#[Route]` attributes across your application and register both the routes and their associated controllers.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Suppose you want to define a route for the `/blog` URL in your application.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] This configuration defines a route called `blog_list` that matches when the user requests the `/blog` URL.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] When the match occurs, the application runs the `list()` method of the `BlogController` class.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The query string of a URL is not considered when matching routes.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In this example, URLs like `/blog?foo=bar` and `/blog?foo=bar&bar=foo` will also match the `blog_list` route.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If you define multiple PHP classes in the same file, Symfony only loads the routes of the first class, ignoring all the other routes.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The route attribute always wins over routes defined in YAML or PHP files and Symfony will always load the route attribute.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The route name (`blog_list`) is not important for now, but it will be essential later when generating URLs.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] You only have to remember that each route name must be unique in the application.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Instead of defining routes in the controller classes, you can define them in a separate YAML or PHP file.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The main advantage is that they don't require any extra dependency.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The main drawback is that you have to work with multiple files when checking the routing of some controller action.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] HTML forms only support `GET` and `POST` methods.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If you're calling a route with a different method from an HTML form, add a hidden field called `_method` with the method to use (e.g.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If you create your forms with Symfony Forms this is done automatically for you when the framework.http_method_override option is `true`.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] For security, you can restrict which HTTP methods can be overridden using the framework.allowed_http_method_override option.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] , which holds the most fundamental information about the route being matched.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] object that represents the current request.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Internally, expressions are compiled down to raw PHP.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Because of this, using the `condition` key causes no extra overhead beyond the time it takes for the underlying PHP to execute.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Conditions are *not* taken into account when generating URLs (which is explained later in this article).
[src:symfony/routing-p01] As your application grows, you'll eventually have a *lot* of routes.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Symfony includes some commands to help you debug routing issues.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The `--sort` option of `debug:router` was introduced in Symfony 8.1.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The other command is called `router:match` and it shows which route will match the given URL.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The previous examples defined routes where the URL never changes (e.g.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] However, it's common to define routes where some parts are variable.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] For example, the URL to display some blog post will probably include the title or slug (e.g.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] `/blog/my-first-post` or `/blog/all-about-symfony`).
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In Symfony routes, variable parts are wrapped in `{ }`.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The name of the variable part (`{slug}` in this example) is used to create a PHP variable where that route content is stored and passed to the controller.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If a user visits the `/blog/my-first-post` URL, Symfony executes the `show()` method in the `BlogController` class and passes a `$slug = 'my-first-post'` argument to the `show()` method.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Routes can define any number of parameters, but each of them can only be used once on each route (e.g.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] `/blog/posts-about-{category}/page/{pageNumber}`).
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Imagine that your application has a `blog_show` route (URL: `/blog/{slug}`) and a `blog_list` route (URL: `/blog/{page}`).
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Given that route parameters accept any value, there's no way to differentiate both routes.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If the user requests `/blog/my-first-post`, both routes will match and Symfony will use the route which was defined first.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The `requirements` option defines the PHP regular expressions that route parameters must match for the entire route to match.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In this example, `[0-9]+` is a regular expression that matches a *digit* of any length.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The Requirement enum contains a collection of commonly used regular-expression constants such as digits, dates and UUIDs which can be used as route parameter requirements.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Route requirements (and route paths too) can include configuration parameters, which is useful to define complex regular expressions once and reuse them in multiple routes.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Parameters also support PCRE Unicode properties, which are escape sequences that match generic character types.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] For example, `\p{Lu}` matches any uppercase character in any language, `\p{Greek}` matches any Greek characters, etc.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If you prefer, requirements can be inlined in each parameter using the syntax `{parameter_name<requirements>}`.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In the previous example, the URL of `blog_list` is `/blog/{page}`.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If users visit `/blog/1`, it will match.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] But if they visit `/blog`, it will **not** match.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] As soon as you add a parameter to a route, it must have a value.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] You can make `blog_list` once again match when the user visits `/blog` by adding a default value for the `{page}` parameter.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] When using attributes, default values are defined in the arguments of the controller action.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Now, when the user visits `/blog`, the `blog_list` route will match and `$page` will default to a value of `1`.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The default value is allowed to not match the requirement.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] You can have more than one optional parameter (e.g.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] `/blog/{slug}/{page}`), but everything after an optional parameter must be optional.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] For example, `/{page}/blog` is a valid path, but `page` will always be required (i.e.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] As it happens with requirements, default values can also be inlined in each parameter using the syntax `{parameter_name?default_value}`.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] To give a `null` default value to any parameter, add nothing after the `?` character (e.g.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If you do this, don't forget to update the types of the related controller arguments to allow passing `null` values (e.g. replace `int $page` by `?int $page`).
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Symfony evaluates routes in the order they are defined.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If the path of a route matches many different patterns, it might prevent other routes from being matched.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In YAML or PHP config files you can move the route definitions up or down in the configuration file to control their priority.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The priority parameter expects an integer value.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Routes with higher priority are sorted before routes with lower priority.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The default value when it is not defined is `0`.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] A common routing need is to convert the value stored in some parameter (e.g. an integer acting as the user ID) into another value (e.g. the object that represents the user).
[src:symfony/routing-p01] This feature is called a "param converter".
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Now, keep the previous route configuration, but change the arguments of the controller action.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If your controller arguments include type-hints for objects (`BlogPost` in this case), the "param converter" makes a database request to find the object using the request parameters (`slug` in this case).
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If no object is found, Symfony generates a 404 response automatically.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The `{slug:post}` syntax maps the route parameter named `slug` to the controller argument named `$post`.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] It also hints the "param converter" to look up the corresponding `BlogPost` object from the database using the slug.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] When mapping multiple entities from route parameters, name collisions can occur.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In this example, the route tries to define two mappings: one for an author and one for a category; both using the same `name` parameter.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] This way, the route parameter names are unique (`authorName` and `categoryName`), and the "param converter" can correctly map them to controller arguments (`$author` and `$category`), loading them both by their name.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] More advanced mappings can be achieved using the `#[MapEntity]` attribute.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Check out the Doctrine param conversion documentation to learn how to customize the database queries used to fetch the object from the route parameter.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] You can use PHP backed enumerations as route parameters because Symfony will convert them automatically to their scalar values.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] This parameter is used to determine which controller and action is executed when the route is matched.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] character and is used to identify a portion of a document.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] An array of query parameters to add to the generated URL.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] You can include these attributes (except `_fragment`) both in individual routes and in route imports.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In the `defaults` option of a route you can optionally define parameters not included in the route configuration.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Route parameters can contain any values except the `/` slash character, because that's the character used to separate the different parts of the URLs.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] For example, if the `token` value in the `/share/{token}` route contains a `/` character, this route won't match.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If the route defines several parameters and you apply this permissive regular expression to all of them, you might get unexpected results.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] For example, if the route definition is `/share/{path}/{token}` and both `path` and `token` accept `/`, then `token` will only get the last part and the rest is matched by `path`.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If the route includes the special `{_format}` parameter, you shouldn't use the `.+` requirement for the parameters that allow slashes.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] For example, if the pattern is `/share/{token}.{_format}` and `{token}` allows any character, the `/share/foo/bar.json` URL will consider `foo/bar.json` as the token and the format will be empty.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] This can be solved by replacing the `.+` requirement by `[^.]+` to allow any character except dots.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Route alias allows you to have multiple names for the same route and can be used to provide backward compatibility for routes that have been renamed.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Now, let's say you want to create a new route called `product_details` that acts exactly the same as `product_show`.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Instead of duplicating the original route, you can create an alias for it.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In this example, both `product_show` and `product_details` routes can be used in the application and will produce the same result.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] YAML and PHP configuration formats are the only ways to define an alias for a route that you do not own.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] You can't do this when using PHP attributes.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] This allows you for example to use your own route name for URL generation, while still targeting a route defined by a third-party bundle.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The alias and the original route do not need to be declared in the same file or format.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Route aliases can be used to provide backward compatibility for routes that have been renamed.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Now, let's say you want to replace the `product_show` route in favor of `product_details` and mark the old one as deprecated.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In the previous example, the alias `product_details` was pointing to `product_show` route.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] To mark the `product_show` route as deprecated, you need to "switch" the alias.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The `product_show` become the alias, and will now point to the `product_details` route.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] This way, the `product_show` alias could be deprecated.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In this example, every time the `product_show` alias is used, a deprecation warning is triggered, advising you to stop using this route and prefer using `product_details`.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The message is actually a message template, which replaces occurrences of the `%alias_id%` placeholder by the route alias name.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] You **must** have at least one occurrence of the `%alias_id%` placeholder in your template.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] It's common for a group of routes to share some options (e.g. all routes related to the blog start with `/blog`) That's why Symfony includes a feature to share route configuration.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] When defining routes as attributes, put the common configuration in the `#[Route]` attribute of the controller class.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In other routing formats, define the common configuration using options when importing the routes.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The `exclude` option only works when the `resource` value is a glob string.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] `'../src/Controller'`) the `exclude` value will be ignored.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In this example, the route of the `index()` action will be called `blog_index` and its URL will be `/blog/{_locale}`.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The route of the `show()` action will be called `blog_show` and its URL will be `/blog/{_locale}/posts/{slug}`.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Both routes will also validate that the `_locale` parameter matches the regular expression defined in the class attribute.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] If any of the prefixed routes defines an empty path, Symfony adds a trailing slash to it.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In the previous example, an empty path prefixed with `/blog` will result in the `/blog/` URL.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The `trailingSlashOnRoot` argument of `CollectionConfigurator::prefix()` was introduced in Symfony 8.1.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Symfony can import routes from different sources and you can even create your own route loader.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] The `Request` object created by Symfony stores all the route configuration (such as the name and parameters) in the "request attributes".
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In services, you can get this information by injecting the RequestStack service.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] In templates, use the Twig global app variable to get the current route name (`app.current_route`) and its parameters (`app.current_route_parameters`).
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Symfony defines some special controllers to render templates and redirect to other routes from the route configuration so you don't have to create a controller action.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Read the section about rendering a template from a route in the main article about Symfony templates.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Historically, URLs have followed the UNIX convention of adding trailing slashes for directories (e.g.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] `https://example.com/foo/`) and removing them to refer to files (`https://example.com/foo`).
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Although serving different contents for both URLs is OK, nowadays it's common to treat both URLs as the same URL and redirect between them.
[src:symfony/routing-p01] Routes can configure a `host` option to require that the HTTP host of the incoming requests matches some specific value.
