[src:symfony/symfony] Symfony aims to speed up the creation and maintenance of web applications and to replace repetitive coding tasks.
[src:symfony/symfony] It's also aimed at building robust applications in an enterprise context, and aims to give developers full control over the configuration: from the directory structure to third-party libraries, almost everything can be customized.
[src:symfony/symfony] To match enterprise development guidelines, Symfony is bundled with additional tools to help developers test, debug and document projects.
[src:symfony/symfony] Symfony has a low performance overhead used with a bytecode cache.
[src:symfony/symfony] Symfony was heavily inspired by the Spring Framework.
[src:symfony/symfony] Symfony is sponsored by SensioLabs, a French software developer and professional services provider.
[src:symfony/symfony] The first name was Sensio Framework, and all classes were therefore prefixed with *sf*.
[src:symfony/symfony] Later, when it was decided to launch it as an open-source framework, the brainstorming resulted in the name symfony (renamed to Symfony from version 2 onward), which matched the existing theme and class name prefixes.
[src:symfony/symfony] Symfony's own website has a comprehensive list of projects using Symfony and a showcase of websites built with Symfony.
[src:symfony/symfony] Symfony manages its releases through a time-based model; a new Symfony release comes out every six months: one in May and one in November.
[src:symfony/symfony] This release process has been adopted as of Symfony 2.2, and all the "rules" explained in this document must be strictly followed as of Symfony 2.4.
[src:symfony/symfony] The standard version of Symfony is maintained for eight months, whereas long-term support (LTS) versions are supported for three years.
[src:symfony/symfony] A new LTS release is published biennially.
[src:symfony/symfony] The latest stable release is version 7.3 and current LTS release is version 6.4.
[src:symfony/twig-template-engine] The same template language is used by the Nunjucks template engine, thus Nunjucks is also supported by the following tools.
[src:symfony/twig-template-engine] Unlike in base PHP, Twig variables do not start with a dollar sign.
[src:symfony/twig-template-engine] The apostrophe (') is the escape character.
[src:symfony/twig-template-engine] The filters provide some treatments on an expression, when placed after it, separated by pipes.
[src:symfony/twig-template-engine] The example below demonstrates some basic features of Twig.
[src:symfony/twig-template-engine] Twig has become a widely adopted templating engine in the PHP ecosystem.
[src:symfony/twig-template-engine] Twig is also employed in many custom PHP applications where secure and readable templating are important.
[src:symfony/twig-template-engine] The similarity of Twig to Jinja and Django templates has also made it familiar to developers coming from Python and other similar ecosystems.
